    "□Consider now the effect of the leaders, namely∂ t f (t, A, w) = Q p (f, f)(t, A, w)+Q ℓ (f, f ℓ)(t, A, w).In this situation, since the microscopic variations of A in (2) and (3) have the same structure, the evolution of the activity level depends on ω p + ω ℓ and a p + a ℓ, namelyd dt m A (t) = λ A ∫ R×I ( Ā(ω p + ω ℓ) + 2ε -(a p + a ℓ)) f (t, A, w)dAdw.",
    "(19)In particular, a version of Proposition 1 holds even in the presence of leaders.",
    "The important difference from the model without leaders is that now the mean opinion is not preserved since leaders tend to bring the agents' opinion closer to theirs, indeedd dt m w (t) = -λ ℓ ∫ R×I 2 ( Āω ℓ + ε)G(w, z)(w -z)f (t, A, w)f ℓ (z)dAdwdz.For the specific case G ≡ 1, we getd dt m w (t) = -λ ℓ ∫ R×I ( Āω ℓ + ε)(w -µ ℓ)f (t, A, w)dAdw(20)and we conjecture the following.Conjecture 1.",
    "Suppose that G ≡ 1, then the average opinion of the population m w (t) converges toward the average opinion of the leaders µ ℓ, when t → +∞.In Subsection 4.2 we will prove Conjecture 1 in a particular, but still realistic, case.2.3.",
    "Opinion polarization and consensus formation."
